import{_ as o,o as t,c as r,a as c,d as e,e as n,b as s}from"./app-de7a4551.js";const i={},a=e("h1",{id:"detroit-s-climate-crisis-—-and-how-to-build-a-resilient-future-everywhere-2",tabindex:"-1"},[e("a",{class:"header-anchor",href:"#detroit-s-climate-crisis-—-and-how-to-build-a-resilient-future-everywhere-2","aria-hidden":"true"},"#"),n(" Detroit's Climate Crisis — and How to Build a Resilient Future Everywhere (2)")],-1),d=s('<p>Detroit is not <em>generally thought</em> of as a city that is at risk for <em>climate impact</em>, but in fact it is.</p><p>We define <code>resilience</code> as places where <code>residents</code> can have their <em>needs met</em> and are free from long-term <em><code>chronic</code> stress</em>, giving them the ability to <code>withstand</code> and recover from <code>acute</code> <code>shocks</code>.</p><p>If you are financially stable, then you are much more likely to withstand and recover from the acute shock of climate change.</p><p>Detroit&#39;s economic <code>inequity</code> and climate <code>vulnerability</code> began over 100 years ago under the <code>guise</code> of innovation.</p><p>Detroit not only <em>led the way</em> for automobiles but manufacturing.</p><p>Manufacturing was a part of our community <code>fabric</code>.</p><p>Industrial sites were <code>nestled</code> in neighborhoods throughout the city so that workers could walk to their factory jobs.</p><p>Our economy was <code>booming</code>.</p><p>And although Detroit was not necessarily equal across racial lines, it was still a city of stable, middle-class neighborhoods.</p><p>All of those sites where there was manufacturing and industrial sites that led to our economic boom, many of those industrial sites stand vacant and abandoned.</p><p>We now have about 19 square miles of vacant land in Detroit.</p><p>These industrial sites have led to dangerous <code>contamination</code>, both to our land and our water and our air.</p><details class="custom-container details"><summary>translation</summary><p><strong>sentence:</strong><br> 人们普遍不认为底特律是一个面临气候影响风险的城市，但事实上确实如此。<br> 我们将复原力定义为居民的需求能够得到满足并且免受长期慢性压力的地方，使他们有能力承受急性冲击并从中恢复。<br> 如果您的财务稳定，那么您更有可能承受气候变化的严重冲击并从中恢复。<br> 底特律的经济不平等和气候脆弱性始于 100 多年前，打着创新的幌子。<br> 底特律不仅在汽车领域处于领先地位，而且在制造业方面也处于领先地位。<br> 制造业是我们社区结构的一部分。<br> 工业用地分布在整个城市的社区中，这样工人们就可以步行去工厂工作。<br> 我们的经济蓬勃发展。<br> 尽管底特律在种族方面不一定平等，但它仍然是一座拥有稳定的中产阶级社区的城市。<br> 所有那些曾经有制造业和工业用地，带动我们经济繁荣的地方，其中许多工业用地都处于空置和废弃状态。<br> 现在底特律有大约 19 平方英里的空置土地。<br> 这些工业场地对我们的土地、水和空气造成了危险的污染。</p><p><strong>phrase:</strong><br> generally thought -&gt; 普遍认为：指一种被广泛接受或普遍认为的观点、看法或理论。<br> climate impact -&gt; 气候影响<br> needs met -&gt; 满足需求：指个人或组织的需求得到满足，达到预期目标。<br> chronic stress -&gt; 慢性应激：长期内部或外部压力因素引起的生理或心理反应。<br> led the way -&gt; 带路：成为第一个前往某个地方的人。/起先导作用：在某个领域或方面起到先导作用。<br><strong>word:</strong><br> resilience<br><code>英 [rɪˈzɪliəns]美 [rɪˈzɪliəns]</code><br> n. 恢复力，复原力；（橡胶等的）弹性</p><p>residents<br><code>英 [ˈrezɪdənts]美 [ˈrezɪdənts]</code></p><blockquote><p>n. 居民；（旅店）房客；住院医生，（美国的）高级专科住院实习医生；（美）寄宿制学校学生；（英国派驻半独立国家的）特派代表；驻外特工（resident 的复数）</p></blockquote><p>chronic<br><code>英 [ˈkrɒnɪk]美 [ˈkrɑːnɪk]</code></p><blockquote><p>adj. （疾病）慢性的，长期的；（问题）一直有的，反复出现的；难以根除的，积习难改的；&lt;英，非正式&gt;糟透的，拙劣的</p></blockquote><p>withstand ( withstanding, withstood, /wɪðˈstænd/ withstands )<br><code>英 [wɪðˈstænd]美 [wɪðˈstænd]</code></p><blockquote><p>v. 顶住，抵住；经受住，承受住（攻击、批评等）；反抗</p></blockquote><p>acute<br><code>英 [əˈkjuːt]美 [əˈkjuːt]</code></p><blockquote><p>adj. 严重的，危险的；急性的，剧烈的；灵敏的；敏锐的，有洞察力的；锐角的；带尖音符的；（声音）高的，尖的</p></blockquote><p>shocks ( shocking, shocked, shocks )<br><code>英 [ʃɒks]美 [ʃɑːks]</code></p><blockquote><p>n. [力]冲击；震动；缓冲装置；蓬乱的一堆；禾束堆（shock 的复数）<br> v. 使震动；使休克；感到震惊；把……堆成禾束堆（shock 的三单形式）</p></blockquote><p>inequity [ 复数 inequities ]<br><code>英 [ɪnˈekwəti]美 [ɪnˈekwəti]</code></p><blockquote><p>n. 不公平，不公正</p></blockquote><p>vulnerability<br><code>英 [ˌvʌlnərəˈbɪləti]美 [ˌvʌlnərəˈbɪləti]</code></p><blockquote><p>n. 易损性，弱点；（桥牌）局况</p></blockquote><p>guise<br><code>英 [ɡaɪz]美 [ɡaɪz]</code></p><blockquote><p>n. 伪装；装束；外观<br> vt. 使化装<br> vi. 伪装</p></blockquote><p>fabric [ 复数 fabrics ]<br><code>英 [ˈfæbrɪk]美 [ˈfæbrɪk]</code></p><blockquote><p>n. 布料，织物；构造，结构；（汽车的）车身，（飞机的）机身</p></blockquote><p>nestled ( nestling, nestled, nestles ) <code>美 [ˈnesld]</code></p><blockquote><p>依偎 舒适而温暖地安定下来（nestle 的过去式和过去分词</p></blockquote><p>booming ( booming, boomed, booms )<br><code>英 [ˈbuːmɪŋ]美 [ˈbuːmɪŋ]</code></p><blockquote><p>adj. 飞速发展的，繁荣的；（声音）低沉洪亮的；奋力撞击的<br> v. 发出巨响，轰鸣；增长，繁荣（boom 的现在分词）</p></blockquote><p>contamination<br><code>英 [kənˌtæmɪˈneɪʃ(ə)n]美 [kənˌtæmɪˈneɪʃ(ə)n]</code></p><blockquote><p>n. 污染</p></blockquote></details>',13);function l(b,u){return t(),r("div",null,[a,c(" 底特律的气候危机以及如何在世界各地建立一个有弹性的未来(2) "),d])}const h=o(i,[["render",l],["__file","30-detroit-climate-crisis-2.html.vue"]]);export{h as default};
